A bone house is still fascinating after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof is like the back of a prehistoric estuary, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn-up fish mullets.
This is the Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the foaming facades and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only with a closer look that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
During the night, the entire facade still works more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same fluffy lines and veiled shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, and even holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the conversion of a house from 1877, the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
The Casa Batlló rental house, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative home of the reality owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were precisely on its riding board.
However, many other artists and artists also cooperated in the design of the facade.
The joint work on the drafts for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in the Park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house came from the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "appearing house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint Georg, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces for the time being.
A little bit bizarre, she's already had her 45-degree negativity.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations at that time and did not let himself be fooled by them.
Before the construction began, he received the appropriate building permit from the city but the details of the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded relief.
The Councillors also encountered, among other things, the fact that construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the city district's invitation to do so, Josep Batlló submitted an application to approve the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the reconstruction, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept to interconnect rooms.
The social part can be completely linked by opening the lounge doors and thus a larger society could comfortably chat without having to give up a certain intimacy in the case of more confidential discussions.
The house received a rather unusual roof and two other floors by Gaudí's conversion, except for a new facade.
Gaudí's game is impressive with the light, as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is disguised and the light courts.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batlló, which was included in the World Heritage List of Unesco in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment made available to the public.
The houseowners only decided on this step in the year and this was on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When one discovered that this is a fairly bearable business, one maintained the visits, yes one extended it also to further common and the attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the building monument is not a pappenstiel, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist exhibits will receive 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds entry prices to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
