The democratic movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
The Latinobarometro survey, carried out in 18 countries, was published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly evident in this year's September and October surveys.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its most important institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has grown by around 6% annually since 2002, the number of democracy advocates rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the severe collapse of last year, such a trend can be seen.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which reduces the regional average (see Graph 2).
About 44% of respondents said that they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, which is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a marked increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
The fact that this took place during the world economic crisis may be that Latin America’s countries only experienced a short recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports by the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and has fallen by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong mood differences from country to country (see diagram 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of the outgoing president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more noticeable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the beginning of the survey have many respondents in Latin America seen a greater problem in their country than in unemployment (see Graph 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member became victims of a crime last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reach the lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic performance is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market sectors: around 71% of respondents reported over-regionally that the private sector was essential for development, with 56% in 2007 (see Graph 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can make progress in its country, compared with 47% last year.
