In 2013, the year of birth of a new currency area in which the beneficiary countries are severely penalised will be forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector will have to take over part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a tough growth course, with high savings and investment rates, measurement of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on indebtedness and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as mentioned by Spain in booming times, will simply not be taken.
The offer is clear.
And we wouldn't mind not understanding it.
It is not just about driving down the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheating ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will change to more tranquillity.
And that we will take advantage of the possibilities offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and its double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of order in his own home is ready for its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like it would change anything.
Among the possibilities considered is that we would not have to leave the euro area fully blocked with a small number of serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and control
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
The exclusion of two real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed about whether it was an unsportsful act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before gambling (their team had already won clearly) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the required penalty at the next league against the Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA's Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach José Mourinho with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten, but in this type of sport - rules.
Part of the debate on the case presented goes back to the fact that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who in his hymn presented nobleness and honor and punished his players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the main role in this, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the Statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a set of rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to bypass its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused by the spirit of sports should be investigated.
The spirit of sport defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the opposing players from taking an unjustified advantage of the opposing team. This was not the case either.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by mistake or regulation, because the circumvention of the rule was not secretly carried out in order to avoid a sanction, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players were waiting and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the defendants drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was neither placed in any less favorable position nor the advantages of the played game were heated because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club doesn't have these players.
The advantage is clearly that the players begin the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also leave. Furthermore, the players get a sanction with this approach and move into the second card cycle, in which they leave with a card accumulation less than in the first cycle.
It is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sports, which includes strategic decisions in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to deal with sanctions (that would actually be a clear case of control), they wanted to choose when they submitted to them.
They made a strategic decision to avoid or escape punishment.
Although the boundary between invention and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the polemics came from two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than, rather, aesthetic.
