Global lighting renewal plan
Yesterday, in Cancun, the UN has proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (FCK) equivalent to almost a third of the additional reduction that needs to be realised in order to stabilise the earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction obligations of the industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCCWs issued to the earth due to lighting would be avoided if the white-emitting pears, which so far represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better, by LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the worldwide fleet.
Last year in Copenhagen, major exhaust emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that would reduce global FCKW emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, this balance would have to be reduced by 5 gts to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from being out of control.
95% of the energy in the white bulbs is emitted in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact light bulbs energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs you reduce this energy demand by twice again.
The compact light bulbs average between 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those brought to the market by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company, by the way, took part in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-flowering pear, suggesting the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new bulbs emit very little heat, they can also function with a rule resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have pointed out that compact light bulbs have reserves, as they contain mercury and therefore they have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless producers provide an acceptance point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulbs, but rather the coal power plants, which emit much more mercury in order to generate the electricity wasted by white bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report presents in detail the profits that each country would achieve thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars annually in the purchase of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired plants whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
